1
00:00:09,160 --> 00:00:11,440
(FOOTSTEPS)

2
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:36,920
So this is one of the last paintings
Van Gogh ever painted.

3
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:38,760
Those final months of his life

4
00:00:38,840 --> 00:00:43,080
were probably the most astonishing
artistic outpouring in history.

5
00:00:43,160 --> 00:00:46,640
It was like Shakespeare
knocking off Othello,

6
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:49,920
Macbeth and King Lear
over the summer hols.

7
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,760
And especially astonishing
because Van Gogh did it

8
00:00:52,840 --> 00:00:55,600
with no hope of praise or reward.

9
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:58,000
- Thanks for bringing me.
- You're welcome.

10
00:00:58,080 --> 00:01:00,640
You're being so nice to me.
Why are you being so nice to me?

11
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:03,520
- I'm always nice to you.
- Not like this.

12
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:04,880
These places you're taking me -

13
00:01:04,960 --> 00:01:08,960
Arcadia, the Trojan Gardens, now this.
I think it's suspicious.

14
00:01:09,040 --> 00:01:11,160
What? It's not! There's nothing
to be suspicious about.

15
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:14,800
OK, I was joking. Why aren't you?

16
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:18,600
CURATOR: Each of these pictures now
is worth tens of millions of pounds.

17
00:01:18,680 --> 00:01:20,840
Yet in his lifetime,
he was a commercial disaster.

18
00:01:20,920 --> 00:01:25,120
Sold only one painting,
and that to the sister of a friend.

19
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:29,000
We have here possibly
the greatest artist of all time,

20
00:01:29,080 --> 00:01:32,320
but when he died, you could have sold
his entire body of work

21
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:35,920
and got about enough money
to buy a sofa.

22
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,920
And a couple of chairs.

23
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:39,680
(LAUGHTER)

24
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:41,600
If you follow me now...

25
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:42,920
- CHILDREN: Who is it?
- It's the doctor!

26
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,720
He was the doctor who took care of
Van Gogh when he started to go mad.

27
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:49,360
- I knew that.
- AMY: Look!

28
00:01:49,440 --> 00:01:51,840
There it is, the actual one.

29
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:55,440
Yes. You can almost feel his hand
painting it right in front of you.

30
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:59,440
Carving the colours into shapes...

31
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:01,480
- Wait a minute.
- What?

32
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:04,200
Well, just look at that.

33
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:06,480
- What?
- Something very not good indeed.

34
00:02:06,600 --> 00:02:10,080
- What thing very not good?
- Look there, in the window of the church.

35
00:02:13,080 --> 00:02:16,120
- Is it a face?
- Yes.

36
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:18,840
And not a nice face at all.

37
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:22,760
I know evil when I see it
and I see it in that window.

38
00:02:22,840 --> 00:02:26,560
CURATOR: It has changed hands
for something in the region of 20...

39
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:30,280
DOCTOR: Excuse me. If I can just interrupt
for one second. Sorry, everyone.

40
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:32,960
Routine inspection,
Ministry of Art and...

41
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:34,960
- Artiness. So, um...
- Dr Black.

42
00:02:35,080 --> 00:02:38,480
Yes, that's right. Do you know when
that picture of the church was painted?

43
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:40,800
Ah, well, ah!
What an interesting question.

44
00:02:40,920 --> 00:02:42,240
- Most people...
- I'm going to have to hurry you. When?

45
00:02:42,320 --> 00:02:44,000
- Exactly?
- As exactly as you can.

46
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:46,160
Without a long speech, if poss.
I'm in a hurry.

47
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:49,200
Well, in that case,
probably somewhere between

48
00:02:49,280 --> 00:02:50,840
- the 1st and 3rd of June.
- What year?

49
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:54,720
1890. Less than a year before...

50
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,200
Before he killed himself.

51
00:02:58,600 --> 00:03:00,520
Thank you, sir. Very helpful indeed.

52
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:04,520
Nice bow tie. Bow ties are cool.

53
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:06,560
- Yours is very...
- Oh, thank you.

54
00:03:06,640 --> 00:03:09,200
Keep telling them stuff.
We need to go.

55
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:12,720
- What about the other pictures?
- Art can wait. This is life and death.

56
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:14,840
We need to talk to Vincent Van Gogh.

57
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:53,280
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

58
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:55,920
(CAT SCREECHES, DOG BARKS)

59
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:00,800
Right, so here's the plan.
We find Vincent,

60
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:03,600
and he leads us straight to the church
and our nasty friend.

61
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:04,760
- Easy-peasy.
- Well, no.

62
00:04:04,840 --> 00:04:07,200
I suspect nothing
will be easy with Mr Van Gogh.

63
00:04:07,280 --> 00:04:10,280
Now, he'll probably be
in the local café -

64
00:04:10,360 --> 00:04:15,160
sort of orangey light,
chairs and tables outside.

65
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:18,520
- Like this?
- That's the one.

66
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:22,480
Or indeed like...that.

67
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:25,400
Yeah, exactly like that.

68
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:28,200
Good evening.

69
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:30,640
Does the name Vincent Van Gogh
ring a bell?

70
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:32,840
Don't mention that man to me.

71
00:04:32,920 --> 00:04:34,880
Excuse me.

72
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:38,720
- Do you know Vincent Van Gogh?
- Unfortunately.

73
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:40,440
AMY: Unfortunately?

74
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:44,640
He's drunk, he's mad
and he never pays his bills.

75
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:47,280
Good painter, though, eh?

76
00:04:47,360 --> 00:04:49,920
(BOTH LAUGH)

77
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,680
MAN: Come on! Come on!

78
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:54,520
One painting for one drink.

79
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,280
That's not a bad deal.

80
00:04:56,360 --> 00:04:58,440
It wouldn't be a bad deal
if the painting were any good.

81
00:04:58,520 --> 00:05:02,320
I can't hang that up on my walls.
It'd scare the customers half to death.

82
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:05,000
It's bad enough having you
in here in person,

83
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:07,960
let alone looming over the customers
day and night in a stupid hat.

84
00:05:08,040 --> 00:05:09,240
You pay money or you get out.

85
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:11,320
- I'IL pay if you like.
- What?

86
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:13,800
Well, if you like,
I'll pay for the drink.

87
00:05:13,880 --> 00:05:15,160
Or I'll pay for the painting,

88
00:05:15,240 --> 00:05:17,440
and you can use the money
to pay for the drink.

89
00:05:19,080 --> 00:05:20,800
Exactly who are you?

90
00:05:20,880 --> 00:05:24,200
Oh, I'm...new in town.

91
00:05:25,760 --> 00:05:28,000
Well, in that case,
you don't know three things.

92
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:29,920
One, I pay for my own drinks,
thank you.

93
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,400
(LAUGHTER)

94
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:33,680
Two, no-one ever buys
any of my paintings

95
00:05:33,760 --> 00:05:35,680
or they would
be laughed out of town,

96
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:39,440
so if you want to stay in town,
I suggest you keep your cash to yourself.

97
00:05:39,520 --> 00:05:41,280
And three, your friend's cute,

98
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:44,240
but you should keep your big nose
out of other people's business.

99
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:46,280
Come on, just one more drink.

100
00:05:46,360 --> 00:05:47,960
- I'll pay tomorrow.
- No.

101
00:05:48,040 --> 00:05:51,920
Or, on the other hand,
slightly more compassionately, yes?

102
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,440
Or, on the other hand, to protect
my business from madmen, no.

103
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:56,480
Or...

104
00:05:56,560 --> 00:06:00,000
Oh, look, just shut up,
the pair of you!

105
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:02,320
I would like a bottle of wine, please,

106
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:05,840
which I will then share
with whomever I choose.

107
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:07,800
That could be good.

108
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:10,920
- That's good by me.
- Good.

109
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:22,520
That accent of yours.
Are you from Holland, like me?

110
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:25,200
- Yes.
- No.

111
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:27,800
She means yes. So, start again.

112
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:30,080
- Hello, I'm the Doctor.
- I knew it!

113
00:06:30,160 --> 00:06:32,320
Sorry?

114
00:06:32,400 --> 00:06:36,280
My brother's always sending doctors,
but you won't be able to help.

115
00:06:36,360 --> 00:06:38,480
No, not that kind of doctor.

116
00:06:38,560 --> 00:06:41,200
Isn't that incredible,
don't you think, Amy?

117
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:43,880
- Absolutely. One of my favourites.
- One of my favourite what's?

118
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:46,840
- You've never seen my work before.
- Ah, yes.

119
00:06:46,920 --> 00:06:51,040
One of my favourite paintings
that I've ever seen. Generally.

120
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:53,680
Then you can't have seen
many paintings, then.

121
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:56,680
I know it's terrible.

122
00:06:56,760 --> 00:06:58,600
It's the best I could do.

123
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,840
Your hair is orange.

124
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:07,000
Yes. So's yours.

125
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:09,640
Yes.

126
00:07:09,720 --> 00:07:15,000
It was more orange,
but now is, of course...less.

127
00:07:15,080 --> 00:07:18,920
So, Vincent,
painted any churches recently?

128
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,400
Any churchy plans? Are churches,
chapels, religiousy stuff like that,

129
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:26,280
something you'd like to get into?
You know, fairly soon?

130
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:31,000
Well, there is one church I'm thinking
of painting when the weather is right.

131
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:32,680
That is very good news.

132
00:07:32,760 --> 00:07:35,240
- (SCREAMING)
- WOMAN: She's been murdered!

133
00:07:35,320 --> 00:07:36,360
Help me!

134
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:38,320
That, on the other hand,
isn't quite such good news.

135
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:40,480
Come on, Amy, Vincent!

136
00:07:42,760 --> 00:07:45,400
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

137
00:07:45,480 --> 00:07:47,600
MAN: She's been ripped to shreds!

138
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:52,440
- Please, let me look. I'm a doctor.
- Who is it?

139
00:07:52,520 --> 00:07:54,520
DOCTOR: Oh, no, no, no.

140
00:07:56,720 --> 00:07:58,160
MAN: Is she dead?

141
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:03,040
Away, all of you vultures!
This is my daughter. Giselle.

142
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:05,840
What monster could have done this?

143
00:08:05,920 --> 00:08:07,760
- Get away from her!
- OK, OK.

144
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:09,520
Get that madman out of here!

145
00:08:09,600 --> 00:08:11,920
(HUBBUB)

146
00:08:14,440 --> 00:08:18,520
You bring this on us. Your madness!
You!

147
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:19,880
He's to blame!

148
00:08:26,320 --> 00:08:27,320
Are you all right?

149
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:31,400
VINCENT: Yes, I'm used to it.

150
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:33,640
Has anything like this murder
happened here before?

151
00:08:33,720 --> 00:08:35,920
Only a week ago.
It's a terrible time.

152
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,680
As I thought, as I thought.
Come on, we'd better get you home.

153
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:43,320
- Where are you staying tonight?
- Oh, you're very kind.

154
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:45,600
(AMY LAUGHS NERVOUSLY)

155
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:54,840
(DEEP SNORTING)

156
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:58,760
- DOCTOR: Dark night, very starry.
- VINCENT: It's not much.

157
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:01,200
I live on my own.

158
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:05,240
But you should be OK for one night.
One night.

159
00:09:05,320 --> 00:09:09,040
- We're going to stay with him?
- Until he paints that church.

160
00:09:10,280 --> 00:09:13,280
- Watch out. That one's wet.
- What?

161
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:30,360
Sorry about all the clutter.

162
00:09:32,440 --> 00:09:33,840
Some clutter.

163
00:09:33,880 --> 00:09:37,400
I've come to accept the only person
who's going to love my paintings is me.

164
00:09:37,480 --> 00:09:38,920
Wow.

165
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,160
I mean, really. Wow.

166
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:44,640
Yeah, I know, it's a mess.
I'll have a proper clear-out.

167
00:09:44,720 --> 00:09:47,040
I must, I really must.

168
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:00,760
Coffee, anyone?

169
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:02,320
DOCTOR: Not for me, actually.

170
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:09,480
You know, you should be careful
with these. They're...precious.

171
00:10:09,560 --> 00:10:12,360
Precious to me.
Not precious to anyone else.

172
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:14,000
AMY: They're precious to me!

173
00:10:14,080 --> 00:10:17,520
Well, you're very kind.
And kindness is most welcome.

174
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:21,360
Right, so, this church, then.
Near here, is it?

175
00:10:21,440 --> 00:10:23,680
What is it with you and the church?

176
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:26,160
Oh, just casually interested in it,
you know.

177
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:30,880
Far from casual. Seems to me
you never talk about anything else.

178
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:32,240
He's a strange one.

179
00:10:32,320 --> 00:10:35,280
OK, let's talk about you.
What are you interested in?

180
00:10:35,360 --> 00:10:38,720
Well, look around - art.

181
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:41,640
It seems to me there's so much more

182
00:10:41,720 --> 00:10:44,240
to the world than the average eye
is allowed to see.

183
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:46,360
I believe, if you look hard,

184
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:50,280
there are more wonders in this universe

185
00:10:50,360 --> 00:10:52,880
than you could ever have dreamed of.

186
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:55,880
You don't have to tell me.

187
00:10:55,960 --> 00:10:58,760
It's colour. Colour that holds the key.

188
00:10:58,840 --> 00:11:01,600
I can hear the colours.

189
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:03,680
Listen to them.

190
00:11:03,760 --> 00:11:08,040
Every time I step outside,
I feel nature is shouting at me,

191
00:11:08,120 --> 00:11:10,280
"Come on. Come and get me. Come on.

192
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:13,120
"Come on! Capture my mystery!"

193
00:11:14,680 --> 00:11:16,360
Maybe you've had enough coffee now.

194
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:18,600
How about some nice calming tea?

195
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:21,920
Let's get you a cup of camomile
or something, shall we? Amy?

196
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,240
- Where's Amy?
- (AMY SCREAMS)

197
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:26,520
No, no. No!

198
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:29,400
Amy? Amy?

199
00:11:29,480 --> 00:11:30,600
What happened?

200
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:32,240
I don't know, I didn't see it.

201
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:34,560
I was having a look at the paintings out
here when something hit me from behind.

202
00:11:34,640 --> 00:11:36,320
It's OK.
He's gone now, and we're here.

203
00:11:36,400 --> 00:11:37,680
No!

204
00:11:38,720 --> 00:11:41,640
Take it easy. Take it easy!

205
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:43,720
What's happening? What's he doing?

206
00:11:43,800 --> 00:11:45,280
I don't know!

207
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:47,160
Oh, dear.

208
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:51,400
(YELLS)

209
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:53,040
Run. Run!

210
00:11:53,120 --> 00:11:54,880
Yeah, yeah, yeah. That's not a bad idea.

211
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:57,320
Amy, get back.
He's having some kind of fit.

212
00:11:57,400 --> 00:11:59,560
I'll try to calm him down.

213
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:02,960
Easy, Vincent, easy.

214
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:06,120
Look, look. It's me, it's me, it's me.
It's the Doctor, look.

215
00:12:06,200 --> 00:12:09,800
No-one else is here. So, Vincent...

216
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:10,880
VINCENT: Look out!

217
00:12:10,960 --> 00:12:14,880
(CREATURE ROARS)

218
00:12:14,960 --> 00:12:17,240
AMY: I can't see anything. What is it?

219
00:12:18,360 --> 00:12:20,200
That is a good question.

220
00:12:20,280 --> 00:12:23,040
- Let me help you.
- You can see him too?

221
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:24,920
Yes...ish.

222
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:28,800
Well, no. Not really.

223
00:12:28,880 --> 00:12:30,960
(CREATURE ROARS)

224
00:12:31,040 --> 00:12:33,560
- You couldn't see him.
- No.

225
00:12:33,640 --> 00:12:35,240
No. Oi!

226
00:12:36,440 --> 00:12:39,280
(DOCTOR YELLS)

227
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:45,360
(CREATURE SCREAMS)

228
00:13:01,960 --> 00:13:04,240
VINCENT: He's gone.

229
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:07,680
Oh, right. Yes, of course.

230
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:09,240
Right.

231
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:12,280
So he's invisible? What did he look like?

232
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:13,320
I'L show you.

233
00:13:13,400 --> 00:13:16,800
Oh, no, no, no!

234
00:13:16,880 --> 00:13:20,720
- What?
- It's just... That was quite a good...

235
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:22,680
Oh, no.

236
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:24,360
On you go.

237
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:43,640
OK.

238
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:46,120
OK.

239
00:13:47,680 --> 00:13:51,280
Right.
Amy, make Mr Van Gogh comfortable.

240
00:13:51,360 --> 00:13:53,920
Don't let any invisible monsters
in through the front door.

241
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:56,160
But it could be outside! Waiting!

242
00:13:56,240 --> 00:13:59,120
Don't worry, I'll risk it.
What's the worst that can happen?

243
00:13:59,200 --> 00:14:01,080
You could get torn into pieces
by a monster you can't see.

244
00:14:01,160 --> 00:14:03,760
Oh, right, yes. That.

245
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:07,600
Don't worry. I'll be back before
you can say, "Where's he got to now?"

246
00:14:12,520 --> 00:14:13,840
DOCTOR: Not that fast!

247
00:14:14,920 --> 00:14:17,800
But pretty fast.

248
00:14:17,880 --> 00:14:19,840
See you around.

249
00:14:22,760 --> 00:14:27,880
(SNORTING AND GRUMBLING)

250
00:14:32,120 --> 00:14:34,120
(DOCTOR WHISTLES)

251
00:14:52,960 --> 00:14:57,000
(FOOTSTEPS)

252
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:02,640
Right. Are you in here somewhere?
I can't apologise enough.

253
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:04,520
I thought you were just a useless gadget.

254
00:15:04,600 --> 00:15:06,560
I thought you were just
an embarrassing present

255
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:11,440
from a dull godmother
with two heads and bad breath. Twice.

256
00:15:11,520 --> 00:15:13,720
How wrong can a man be?

257
00:15:29,440 --> 00:15:31,080
Good.

258
00:15:31,160 --> 00:15:33,200
OK, you're working.

259
00:15:33,280 --> 00:15:36,720
Now, see what you make of this.

260
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:38,720
Who is that?

261
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:44,360
No, I know it's not that.
There are thousands of them,

262
00:15:44,440 --> 00:15:45,840
you can see them plain as day.

263
00:15:45,920 --> 00:15:49,080
No. Definitely not. This is the problem
with the Impressionists -

264
00:15:49,160 --> 00:15:50,760
not accurate enough.

265
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:53,200
This would never happen
with Gainsborough

266
00:15:53,280 --> 00:15:55,040
or one of those "proper"” painters.

267
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:56,880
Sorry, Vincent.

268
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:01,320
You'll just have
to draw something better.

269
00:16:08,400 --> 00:16:10,120
That's better, old girl.

270
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:14,400
Time delay, but you always
get it right in the end. Good.

271
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:16,160
Let's find out who this is, then.

272
00:16:16,240 --> 00:16:19,200
Whoa, there you are, you poor thing.

273
00:16:19,280 --> 00:16:21,080
You brutal, murderous...

274
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:23,520
abandoned thing.

275
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:27,360
I hope we meet again soon
so I can take you home.

276
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:29,720
(CREATURE ROARS)

277
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:32,240
Maybe not that soon.

278
00:16:58,040 --> 00:17:01,040
(CREATURE SCREECHES)

279
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:14,040
(WAILING AND CLATTERING)

280
00:17:26,480 --> 00:17:28,040
(BOTH SHRIEK)

281
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:32,560
Never do that! You scared
the living daylights out of me.

282
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:34,360
Sorry. I got bored.

283
00:17:34,440 --> 00:17:37,000
As much as you admire
his command of colour and shape,

284
00:17:37,080 --> 00:17:40,000
it is hard to get fond of
Vincent Van Gogh's snoring.

285
00:17:40,080 --> 00:17:41,800
(SNORING)

286
00:17:42,960 --> 00:17:46,240
DOCTOR: Wakey-wakey! Rise and shine!

287
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:48,960
Breakfast is served in the courtyard.

288
00:17:49,040 --> 00:17:51,960
Whoa! What a morning.

289
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:55,520
Come on.

290
00:17:55,600 --> 00:17:58,200
And Amy's got a little surprise for you.

291
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:02,400
I thought I'd brighten things up
to thank you for saving me last night.

292
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:03,680
Ah!

293
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:05,640
I thought you might like, you know,

294
00:18:05,720 --> 00:18:09,600
possibly to perhaps paint them
or something? Might be a thought.

295
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:10,720
Yes.
Well, they're not my favourite flower.

296
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:14,440
- You don't like sunflowers?
- No, it's not that I don't like them.

297
00:18:14,520 --> 00:18:16,600
I find them complex.

298
00:18:16,680 --> 00:18:20,520
Always somewhere between
living and dying.

299
00:18:20,600 --> 00:18:23,920
Half-human as they turn to the sun.
A little disgusting.

300
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:25,560
But, you know,

301
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:27,320
they are a challenge.

302
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:30,000
And one I'm pretty sure you'll rise to.

303
00:18:30,120 --> 00:18:32,680
But, moving on,
there's something I need to show you.

304
00:18:34,160 --> 00:18:36,040
VINCENT: That's him!

305
00:18:36,120 --> 00:18:37,400
And the eyes.

306
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:39,160
Without mercy.

307
00:18:39,240 --> 00:18:42,960
This is a creature called the Krafayis.

308
00:18:43,040 --> 00:18:45,400
They travel in space,
they travel as a pack.

309
00:18:45,480 --> 00:18:47,760
Scavenging across the universe.

310
00:18:47,840 --> 00:18:49,800
Sometimes one of them gets left behind,

311
00:18:49,880 --> 00:18:52,760
and because they are a brutal race,
the others never come back.

312
00:18:52,840 --> 00:18:56,400
So, dotted all around the universe
are individual,

313
00:18:56,480 --> 00:18:59,960
utterly merciless,
utterly abandoned Krafayis.

314
00:19:00,040 --> 00:19:03,600
And what they do is...
Well, kill, until they're killed.

315
00:19:03,680 --> 00:19:07,120
Which they usually aren't.
Because other creatures can't see them.

316
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:09,600
- But I can.
- Yes. And that's why

317
00:19:09,680 --> 00:19:14,680
we are in a unique position today,
my friend, to end this reign of terror.

318
00:19:14,760 --> 00:19:16,760
So, feeling like
painting the church today?

319
00:19:16,840 --> 00:19:19,000
What about the monster?

320
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:22,680
Take my word for it.
If you paint it, he will come.

321
00:19:24,240 --> 00:19:27,480
- OK. I'll get my things.
- In your own time.

322
00:19:27,560 --> 00:19:30,280
I promise you, we'll be out
of your hair by this time tomorrow.

323
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:41,440
- This is risky.
- Riskier than normal?

324
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:43,320
Well, think about it.

325
00:19:43,440 --> 00:19:46,960
This is the middle of Vincent Van Gogh's
greatest year of painting.

326
00:19:47,080 --> 00:19:49,000
If we're not careful,
the net result of our pleasant little trip

327
00:19:49,080 --> 00:19:53,080
will be the brutal murder
of the greatest artist who ever lived.

328
00:19:53,160 --> 00:19:56,400
Half the pictures on the wall
of the Musée D'Orsay will disappear.

329
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:01,480
And it will be our fault.

330
00:20:06,560 --> 00:20:07,600
Vincent?

331
00:20:08,640 --> 00:20:10,400
Vincent!

332
00:20:15,960 --> 00:20:18,280
(QUIET WEEPING)

333
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:23,680
Vincent, can I help?

334
00:20:25,560 --> 00:20:27,120
It's so clear you cannot help.

335
00:20:27,200 --> 00:20:30,280
And when you leave -
and everyone always leaves -

336
00:20:30,360 --> 00:20:35,400
I will be left once more
with an empty heart and no hope.

337
00:20:35,480 --> 00:20:39,800
DOCTOR: My experience
is that there is, you know,

338
00:20:39,880 --> 00:20:45,440
- surprisingly, always hope.
- Then your experience is incomplete.

339
00:20:45,520 --> 00:20:47,560
I know how it will end.

340
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:51,360
And it will not end well.

341
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:00,880
Come on. Come out, let's go outside.

342
00:21:00,960 --> 00:21:02,720
Out!

343
00:21:02,800 --> 00:21:05,000
You get out!

344
00:21:05,080 --> 00:21:08,440
What are you doing here?
What are you doing here?

345
00:21:08,520 --> 00:21:12,960
Very well. I'll leave. I'll leave you.

346
00:21:13,040 --> 00:21:16,840
(VINCENT SOBS)

347
00:21:17,080 --> 00:21:18,920
What's happening?

348
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:21,120
We're leaving.

349
00:21:22,200 --> 00:21:24,200
Everyone knows he's a delicate man.

350
00:21:24,280 --> 00:21:30,320
Just months from now, he'll...
he'll take his own life.

351
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:36,840
Don't say that. Please.

352
00:21:47,080 --> 00:21:48,880
Come on.
We have to do this on our own.

353
00:21:48,960 --> 00:21:52,840
Go to the church at the right time
and hope the monster still turns up.

354
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:00,040
I'm ready. Let's go.

355
00:22:06,680 --> 00:22:09,840
- I'm sorry you're so sad.
- But I'm not.

356
00:22:09,920 --> 00:22:13,160
Sometimes these moods torture me
for weeks, for months.

357
00:22:13,240 --> 00:22:14,440
But I'm good now.

358
00:22:14,520 --> 00:22:18,720
If Amy Pond can soldier on,
then so can Vincent Van Gogh.

359
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:21,560
I'm not soldiering on. I'm fine.

360
00:22:21,640 --> 00:22:23,840
Oh, Amy.

361
00:22:23,920 --> 00:22:26,160
I hear the song of your sadness.

362
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:28,680
You've lost someone, I think.

363
00:22:28,760 --> 00:22:30,720
I'm not sad.

364
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:33,600
Then why are you crying?

365
00:22:36,920 --> 00:22:39,400
It's all right. I understand.

366
00:22:39,480 --> 00:22:41,600
I'm not sure I do.

367
00:22:41,680 --> 00:22:44,120
OK. OK!

368
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:47,120
So, now, we must have a plan.
When the creature returns...

369
00:22:47,200 --> 00:22:49,240
Then we shall fight him again.

370
00:22:49,320 --> 00:22:52,440
Well, yes, tick.

371
00:22:52,520 --> 00:22:54,480
But last night we were lucky.

372
00:22:54,560 --> 00:22:56,880
Amy could have been killed.

373
00:22:56,960 --> 00:23:00,320
So this time, for a start, we have
to make sure I can see him too.

374
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:03,080
And how are we meant to do that,
suddenly?

375
00:23:03,160 --> 00:23:06,920
The answer's in this box. I had
an excellent, if smelly, godmother.

376
00:23:10,880 --> 00:23:14,600
VINCENT: Oh, no.
It's that poor girl from the village.

377
00:23:35,240 --> 00:23:37,440
You do have a plan...don't you?

378
00:23:37,520 --> 00:23:40,080
No.

379
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:42,800
It's a thing - it's like a plan,
but with more greyness.

380
00:23:50,720 --> 00:23:55,560
DOCTOR: And you'll be sure to tell me
if you see any, you know, monsters.

381
00:23:55,640 --> 00:23:59,720
Yes. While I may be mad,
I'm not stupid.

382
00:23:59,800 --> 00:24:02,440
No, quite.

383
00:24:02,520 --> 00:24:04,440
And, to be honest...

384
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:08,360
I'm not sure about mad either.

385
00:24:08,440 --> 00:24:12,200
It seems to me
depression is a very complex...

386
00:24:12,280 --> 00:24:15,560
Sssssh.

387
00:24:15,640 --> 00:24:18,240
I'm working.

388
00:24:18,320 --> 00:24:19,960
Well, yes.

389
00:24:20,040 --> 00:24:22,800
Paint!

390
00:24:22,880 --> 00:24:24,360
Do painting!

391
00:24:26,360 --> 00:24:29,840
I remember watching Michelangelo
painting the Sistine Chapel.

392
00:24:29,920 --> 00:24:32,760
Wow! What a whinger. I kept saying to him,

393
00:24:32,840 --> 00:24:35,720
"Look, if you're scared of heights,
you shouldn't have taken the job."

394
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:36,800
AMY: Ssh!

395
00:24:36,880 --> 00:24:40,280
And Picasso. What a ghastly old goat.

396
00:24:40,360 --> 00:24:45,360
I kept telling him,
"Concentrate, Pablo, it's one eye,

397
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:48,280
"either side of the face."

398
00:24:48,360 --> 00:24:50,640
AMY: Quiet.

399
00:24:50,720 --> 00:24:53,800
Is this how time normally passes?

400
00:24:53,880 --> 00:24:57,080
Really slowly.

401
00:24:57,160 --> 00:24:58,800
In the right order.

402
00:25:00,280 --> 00:25:04,720
If there's one thing I can't stand,
it's an unpunctual alien attack.

403
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:07,360
Are you OK? You seem a bit,

404
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:09,240
if I didn't know better, I'd say nervous.

405
00:25:09,320 --> 00:25:12,640
DOCTOR: There's something not right,
and I can't quite put my finger on it.

406
00:25:12,720 --> 00:25:16,360
There! He's at the window.

407
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:19,080
- Where?
- There, on the right.

408
00:25:19,160 --> 00:25:21,800
As I thought. Come on.

409
00:25:21,880 --> 00:25:22,840
I'm going in.

410
00:25:22,920 --> 00:25:24,760
- Well, I'm coming too.
- No!

411
00:25:24,840 --> 00:25:28,680
You're Vincent Van Gogh.

412
00:25:28,760 --> 00:25:30,360
No.

413
00:25:30,440 --> 00:25:31,880
But you're not armed.

414
00:25:31,960 --> 00:25:33,400
-I am.
- What with?

415
00:25:33,480 --> 00:25:36,600
Overconfidence, this,
and a small screw driver. I'm sorted.

416
00:25:36,680 --> 00:25:39,720
Just have to find the right
crosactic setting and stun him with it.

417
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:43,120
Sonic never fails.
Anyway, Amy, only one thought,

418
00:25:43,240 --> 00:25:49,280
one simple instruction -
don't follow me under any circumstances.

419
00:25:49,360 --> 00:25:50,920
I won't.

420
00:25:55,600 --> 00:25:58,280
- Will you follow him?
- Of course!

421
00:25:59,960 --> 00:26:01,320
I love you.

422
00:26:26,840 --> 00:26:28,960
(BEEPING)

423
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:58,480
(LOW GROWLING)

424
00:27:21,960 --> 00:27:25,480
- Has he moved?
- No. Just shifted to the next window.

425
00:27:27,040 --> 00:27:28,480
But wait!

426
00:27:28,560 --> 00:27:30,400
He's turning now.

427
00:27:41,760 --> 00:27:44,040
Damn. He's moved.

428
00:27:44,120 --> 00:27:45,840
(DOCTOR SCREAMS)

429
00:27:45,920 --> 00:27:47,520
- Doctor!
- VINCENT: Amy!

430
00:27:53,320 --> 00:27:55,160
(KRAFAYIS GROWLS)

431
00:28:00,360 --> 00:28:02,280
- Doctor!
- Argh! I thought I told you...

432
00:28:02,360 --> 00:28:05,280
Never mind. We'll talk about it later.
Quick. In here.

433
00:28:06,920 --> 00:28:10,160
(FOOTSTEPS THUD)

434
00:28:10,240 --> 00:28:14,040
DOCTOR (WHISPERING): Absolutely quiet.

435
00:28:14,120 --> 00:28:17,320
(AMY BREATHES)

436
00:28:19,440 --> 00:28:22,320
Can you breath a little quieter, please?

437
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:24,760
No!

438
00:28:24,840 --> 00:28:26,280
(KRAFAYIS GROWLS)

439
00:28:32,200 --> 00:28:34,480
- He's gone past.
- Ssh.

440
00:28:44,040 --> 00:28:45,400
(KRAFAYIS GROWLS LOUDLY)

441
00:28:45,480 --> 00:28:46,440
(AMY SCREAMS)

442
00:28:46,520 --> 00:28:48,120
I think he heard us.

443
00:28:49,200 --> 00:28:51,320
That is impressive hearing he's got.

444
00:28:51,400 --> 00:28:52,440
(GROWLS)

445
00:28:53,720 --> 00:28:56,480
What's less impressive
are our chances of survival.

446
00:28:56,560 --> 00:28:57,560
(AMY SCREAMS)

447
00:28:57,640 --> 00:29:00,240
VINCENT: Hey!
Are you looking for me, sonny?

448
00:29:01,800 --> 00:29:04,080
Come on! Over here.

449
00:29:04,160 --> 00:29:06,360
Because I'm right here waiting for you.

450
00:29:14,360 --> 00:29:17,160
Come on. Quickly! Get behind me.

451
00:29:17,240 --> 00:29:18,200
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRS)

452
00:29:18,280 --> 00:29:20,840
- Doing anything?
- Uh-uh.

453
00:29:20,920 --> 00:29:22,680
AMY: Come on!

454
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:24,920
Where is he?

455
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:28,280
Where do you think he is,
you idiot? Use your head.

456
00:29:28,360 --> 00:29:31,040
- Anything?
- Nothing.

457
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:33,040
In fact,
he seemed to rather enjoy it.

458
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:35,840
- Ooh.
- (SNARLING)

459
00:29:35,920 --> 00:29:37,640
Duck! Left!

460
00:29:38,960 --> 00:29:41,160
- (AMY SCREAMS)
- Right, sorry.

461
00:29:41,240 --> 00:29:42,200
Agh!

462
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:43,920
Your right, my left.

463
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:46,320
This is no good at all.
Run like crazy and regroup.

464
00:29:46,400 --> 00:29:48,800
Oh, come on, in here.

465
00:30:02,680 --> 00:30:04,320
Right. OK.

466
00:30:04,400 --> 00:30:06,840
- Here's the plan. Amy, Rory...
- Who?

467
00:30:06,920 --> 00:30:08,880
Sorry, um, Vincent.

468
00:30:08,960 --> 00:30:10,880
- What is the plan?
- I don't know, actually.

469
00:30:10,960 --> 00:30:12,240
My only definite plan is that in future,

470
00:30:12,320 --> 00:30:14,160
I'm just using this screwdriver
for screwing in screws.

471
00:30:14,240 --> 00:30:16,680
Give me a second. I'll be back.

472
00:30:17,760 --> 00:30:20,520
- I suppose we could try talking to him.
- Talking to him?!

473
00:30:20,600 --> 00:30:22,960
Well, yes. Might be interesting
to know his side of the story.

474
00:30:23,040 --> 00:30:24,000
(ROARING)

475
00:30:24,080 --> 00:30:27,520
Yes, though maybe he's not really
in the mood for conversation

476
00:30:27,600 --> 00:30:29,280
right at this precise moment.

477
00:30:29,360 --> 00:30:31,400
(BANGING AND GROWLING)

478
00:30:33,120 --> 00:30:36,800
Well, no harm trying. Listen.
Listen!

479
00:30:38,800 --> 00:30:40,440
I know you can understand me.

480
00:30:40,560 --> 00:30:44,880
Even though I know you won't
understand why you can understand me.

481
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:49,240
I also know that no-one's talked to you
for a pretty long stretch,

482
00:30:49,320 --> 00:30:52,720
but please...listen.

483
00:30:54,960 --> 00:30:57,680
I also don't belong on this planet.

484
00:30:57,760 --> 00:31:01,240
I also am...alone.

485
00:31:02,320 --> 00:31:06,200
If you trust me, I'm sure
we can come to some kind of, you know,

486
00:31:06,280 --> 00:31:07,840
understanding.

487
00:31:07,920 --> 00:31:11,560
And then... And then, who knows?

488
00:31:11,640 --> 00:31:13,880
(SHATTERING)

489
00:31:17,200 --> 00:31:20,800
(ROARING)

490
00:31:22,160 --> 00:31:23,640
Over here, mate!

491
00:31:25,320 --> 00:31:27,000
What's it up to now?

492
00:31:27,080 --> 00:31:30,160
It's moving round the room.
Feeling its way around.

493
00:31:32,120 --> 00:31:35,080
- What?
- It's like it's trapped.

494
00:31:35,160 --> 00:31:38,160
It's moving round
the edges of the room.

495
00:31:39,720 --> 00:31:42,640
AMY: I can't see a thing.

496
00:31:44,200 --> 00:31:46,120
I am really stupid.

497
00:31:46,200 --> 00:31:49,800
Oh, get a grip! This is not a moment
to re-evaluate your self-esteem.

498
00:31:49,880 --> 00:31:54,280
No, I am really stupid
and I'm growing old.

499
00:31:54,360 --> 00:31:56,800
Why does it attack,
but never eat its victims?

500
00:31:56,880 --> 00:31:59,320
And why was it abandoned by its pack
and left here to die?

501
00:31:59,400 --> 00:32:04,520
And why is it feeling its way helplessly
around the walls of the room?

502
00:32:04,600 --> 00:32:07,200
It can't see, it's blind.

503
00:32:07,280 --> 00:32:09,600
And that, of course, explains
why it has such perfect hearing!

504
00:32:09,680 --> 00:32:12,200
Which unfortunately also
explains why it is now

505
00:32:12,280 --> 00:32:14,800
turning around
and heading straight for us.

506
00:32:14,880 --> 00:32:16,840
Vincent. Vincent, what's happening?

507
00:32:16,920 --> 00:32:19,680
It's charging now.
Get back. Get back!

508
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:23,200
Wabh!

509
00:32:26,240 --> 00:32:29,160
- (SQUELCHING)
- Argh!

510
00:32:31,080 --> 00:32:35,480
(WAILING)

511
00:32:39,640 --> 00:32:41,720
He wasn't without mercy at all.

512
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:43,400
He was without sight.

513
00:32:44,960 --> 00:32:46,480
I didn't mean that to happen.

514
00:32:46,560 --> 00:32:49,400
I only meant to wound it,
I never meant to...

515
00:32:49,480 --> 00:32:51,680
(GURGLING)

516
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:53,400
He's trying to say something.

517
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:56,840
What is it?

518
00:32:56,920 --> 00:33:00,400
I'm having trouble making it out,
but I think he's saying,

519
00:33:00,480 --> 00:33:04,360
"I'm afraid. I'm afraid."”

520
00:33:08,480 --> 00:33:10,120
There, there.

521
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:11,480
Ssh! Ssh!

522
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:15,520
It's OK. It's OK. You'll be fine. Ssh!

523
00:33:18,560 --> 00:33:21,640
(SIGHS)

524
00:33:26,440 --> 00:33:28,960
He was frightened.

525
00:33:29,040 --> 00:33:30,800
And he lashed out

526
00:33:30,880 --> 00:33:35,120
like humans, who lash out
when they're frightened.

527
00:33:35,200 --> 00:33:37,400
Like the villagers who scream at me.

528
00:33:38,960 --> 00:33:41,520
Like the children
who throw stones at me.

529
00:33:43,400 --> 00:33:47,760
You know, sometimes winning -
winning is no fun at all.

530
00:34:06,720 --> 00:34:08,560
Hold my hand, Doctor.

531
00:34:10,560 --> 00:34:13,480
Try to see what I see.

532
00:34:13,560 --> 00:34:17,640
We are so lucky we are still alive
to see this beautiful world.

533
00:34:17,720 --> 00:34:19,160
Look at the sky.

534
00:34:19,240 --> 00:34:24,000
It's not dark and black
and without character.

535
00:34:24,080 --> 00:34:26,120
The black is in fact deep blue.

536
00:34:26,200 --> 00:34:29,280
And over there, lighter blue.

537
00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:32,120
And blowing through
the blueness and the blackness,

538
00:34:32,200 --> 00:34:34,400
the wind swirling through the air

539
00:34:34,480 --> 00:34:38,360
and then shining, burning,
bursting through - the stars!

540
00:34:38,440 --> 00:34:40,760
Can you see
how they roar their light?

541
00:34:42,400 --> 00:34:44,760
Everywhere we look,

542
00:34:44,840 --> 00:34:49,080
the complex magic of nature
blazes before our eyes.

543
00:34:51,640 --> 00:34:54,320
I've seen many things, my friend.

544
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:55,800
But you're right.

545
00:34:57,800 --> 00:35:02,400
Nothing quite as wonderful
as the things you see.

546
00:35:11,280 --> 00:35:13,560
I will miss you terribly.

547
00:35:26,320 --> 00:35:28,960
I only wish I had something
of real value to give you.

548
00:35:29,040 --> 00:35:31,600
(DOCTOR GIGGLES)

549
00:35:31,680 --> 00:35:36,920
Oh, no, no. I could never accept
such an extraordinary gift.

550
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:39,360
Very well.

551
00:35:39,440 --> 00:35:41,440
You are not the first
to decline the offer.

552
00:35:41,520 --> 00:35:44,400
Amy, the blessed, the wonderful.

553
00:35:45,960 --> 00:35:49,600
Be good to yourself
and be kind to yourself.

554
00:35:49,680 --> 00:35:50,960
I'L try my best.

555
00:35:51,040 --> 00:35:54,120
And maybe give the beard a little trim
before you next kiss someone.

556
00:35:54,200 --> 00:35:57,400
(LAUGHS) T will. I will.

557
00:35:57,480 --> 00:35:59,640
And if you tire
of this Doctor of yours, return.

558
00:35:59,720 --> 00:36:02,640
- And we will have children by the dozen.
- Eek!

559
00:36:04,200 --> 00:36:05,680
Doctor, my friend...

560
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:09,400
we have fought monsters together
and we have won.

561
00:36:09,480 --> 00:36:13,680
On my own,
I fear I may not do as well.

562
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:30,320
Are you thinking what I'm thinking?

563
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:32,920
I was thinking I may need some food
or something before we leave.

564
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,160
Well, no, you're not thinking
exactly what I'm thinking.

565
00:36:36,240 --> 00:36:37,720
Vincent!

566
00:36:40,560 --> 00:36:43,560
Got something I'd like to show you.

567
00:36:43,640 --> 00:36:45,800
Maybe just tidy yourself up
a bit first.

568
00:36:49,360 --> 00:36:52,920
Now, you know we've had quite
a few chats about the possibility

569
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:56,200
there might be more to life
than normal people imagine?

570
00:36:56,280 --> 00:36:58,320
Yes.

571
00:36:58,400 --> 00:37:02,280
- Well, brace yourself, Vinny.
- (AMY LAUGHS)

572
00:37:30,880 --> 00:37:32,800
How come 7777 the crazy one...

573
00:37:32,880 --> 00:37:35,320
and you two have stayed sane?

574
00:37:39,960 --> 00:37:44,080
- What do these things all do?
- Oh, a huge variety of things.

575
00:37:44,160 --> 00:37:47,600
This one here, for instance,
plays soothing music.

576
00:37:47,680 --> 00:37:49,600
(# STRAUSS: Emperor Waltz)

577
00:37:49,680 --> 00:37:53,320
While this one makes
a huge amount of noise.

578
00:37:53,400 --> 00:37:55,840
(DISTORTED ZOOMING)

579
00:37:55,920 --> 00:37:58,200
And this one makes
everything go absolutely Tonto.

580
00:38:06,040 --> 00:38:07,000
And this one?

581
00:38:07,080 --> 00:38:11,720
- That's a friction contrafibulator!
- And this?

582
00:38:11,800 --> 00:38:14,720
That's ketchup,
and that one's mustard.

583
00:38:14,800 --> 00:38:16,240
Mmm. Nice!

584
00:38:16,320 --> 00:38:18,800
Come on. Back to the café
and you can tell me

585
00:38:18,880 --> 00:38:21,760
about all the wonders
of the universe.

586
00:38:21,840 --> 00:38:23,640
Good idea.
Although, actually,

587
00:38:23,720 --> 00:38:26,720
there's a little something
I'd like to show you first.

588
00:38:26,800 --> 00:38:29,840
(SIREN PASSING)

589
00:38:31,880 --> 00:38:33,440
Where are we?

590
00:38:33,520 --> 00:38:35,760
Paris. 2010 AD.

591
00:38:35,840 --> 00:38:38,440
And this is the mighty
Musée d'Orsay.

592
00:38:38,520 --> 00:38:40,560
Home to many of the greatest
paintings in history.

593
00:38:40,640 --> 00:38:43,480
- Oh, that's wonderful.
- (RADIO PLAYS MUSIC)

594
00:38:43,560 --> 00:38:45,880
Ignore that. I've got something
more important to show you.

595
00:38:46,160 --> 00:38:47,600
(# ATHLETE: Chances)

596
00:38:47,680 --> 00:38:52,680
# Take all your chances while you can

597
00:38:56,360 --> 00:39:01,560
# You never know
when they'll pass you by

598
00:39:04,400 --> 00:39:11,120
# Like a sum
the mathematician cannot solve

599
00:39:13,240 --> 00:39:19,920
# Like me trying my hardest to explain

600
00:39:37,040 --> 00:39:40,880
# It's all about your

601
00:39:40,960 --> 00:39:45,360
# Cries and kisses

602
00:39:45,440 --> 00:39:49,120
# Those first steps that

603
00:39:50,280 --> 00:39:54,360
# I can't calculate... #

604
00:39:54,440 --> 00:39:56,440
- Dr Black...?
- Yes.

605
00:39:56,520 --> 00:39:58,920
We met a few days ago.

606
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:01,640
I asked you about
the Church At Auvers.

607
00:40:01,720 --> 00:40:05,560
- Oh, yes. Glad to be of help.
- You were nice about my tie.

608
00:40:05,640 --> 00:40:08,680
Yes. And today is another cracker,
if I may say so.

609
00:40:08,760 --> 00:40:12,600
But I just wondered,
between you and me, in 100 words,

610
00:40:12,680 --> 00:40:16,880
where do you think Van Gogh rates
in the history of art?

611
00:40:16,960 --> 00:40:21,360
Well, um...big question.

612
00:40:21,440 --> 00:40:25,440
But, to me, Van Gogh
is the finest painter of them all.

613
00:40:25,520 --> 00:40:31,160
Certainly, the most popular
great painter of all time,

614
00:40:31,240 --> 00:40:32,720
the most beloved.

615
00:40:32,800 --> 00:40:35,400
His command of colour,
the most magnificent.

616
00:40:35,520 --> 00:40:41,960
He transformed the pain of
his tormented life into ecstatic beauty.

617
00:40:42,040 --> 00:40:46,640
Pain is easy to portray,
but to use your passion and pain

618
00:40:46,720 --> 00:40:51,640
to portray the ecstasy and joy
and magnificence of our world -

619
00:40:51,720 --> 00:40:53,360
no-one had ever done it before.

620
00:40:53,440 --> 00:40:56,480
Perhaps no-one ever will again.

621
00:40:56,560 --> 00:41:03,000
To my mind, that strange, wild man
who roamed the fields of Provence

622
00:41:03,080 --> 00:41:06,200
was not only the world's
greatest artist,

623
00:41:06,280 --> 00:41:11,280
but also one of the greatest men
who ever lived.

624
00:41:13,720 --> 00:41:17,760
Vincent. I'm sorry.
I'm sorry. Is it too much?

625
00:41:18,840 --> 00:41:22,880
No. They are tears of joy.

626
00:41:25,560 --> 00:41:28,000
Thank you, sir.

627
00:41:28,080 --> 00:41:31,720
- Thank you.
- You're welcome. You're welcome.

628
00:41:31,800 --> 00:41:34,120
Sorry about the beard.

629
00:41:35,280 --> 00:41:39,960
# ... It's all about your

630
00:41:40,040 --> 00:41:43,280
# Cries and kisses

631
00:41:43,360 --> 00:41:47,360
# It's all about you. #

632
00:41:52,240 --> 00:41:53,800
This changes everything.

633
00:41:53,880 --> 00:41:56,880
I'UL step out tomorrow with my easel
on my back a different man.

634
00:41:56,960 --> 00:41:59,240
Though I still can't believe
one of the Haystacks

635
00:41:59,320 --> 00:42:01,040
was in the museum.
How embarrassing.

636
00:42:01,120 --> 00:42:04,560
It's been a great adventure
and a great honour.

637
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:07,640
You've turned out to be
the first doctor

638
00:42:07,720 --> 00:42:10,040
ever actually to make
a difference to my life.

639
00:42:10,120 --> 00:42:12,560
I'm delighted.
I won't ever forget you.

640
00:42:14,520 --> 00:42:17,040
And you are sure
marriage is out of the question?

641
00:42:17,120 --> 00:42:18,120
This time.

642
00:42:20,280 --> 00:42:22,360
I'm not really the marrying kind.

643
00:42:26,920 --> 00:42:29,600
AMY: Come on. Let's go back
to the gallery right now.

644
00:42:53,040 --> 00:42:56,880
Time can be rewritten.
I know it can. Come on!

645
00:42:56,960 --> 00:43:00,880
Oh, the long life
of Vincent Van Gogh.

646
00:43:00,960 --> 00:43:04,560
- There'll be hundreds of new paintings.
- I'm not sure there will.

647
00:43:05,960 --> 00:43:07,560
Come on!

648
00:43:18,560 --> 00:43:22,480
DR BLACK: We have here the last work
of Vincent Van Gogh,

649
00:43:22,560 --> 00:43:25,440
who committed suicide at only 37.

650
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:29,560
He is now acknowledged to be
one of the foremost artists of all time.

651
00:43:29,640 --> 00:43:31,840
If you follow me now...

652
00:43:35,600 --> 00:43:38,640
So you were right.
No new paintings.

653
00:43:41,600 --> 00:43:43,360
We didn't make a difference at all.

654
00:43:43,440 --> 00:43:46,360
I wouldn't say that.

655
00:43:46,440 --> 00:43:52,480
The way I see it, every life is
a pile of good things and bad things.

656
00:43:52,560 --> 00:43:53,760
Hey.

657
00:43:55,160 --> 00:43:59,680
The good things don't always...
soften the bad things.

658
00:43:59,800 --> 00:44:02,880
But vice versa - the bad things
don't necessarily spoil the good things

659
00:44:02,960 --> 00:44:05,120
or make them unimportant.

660
00:44:06,400 --> 00:44:10,320
And we definitely added
to his pile of good things.

661
00:44:11,640 --> 00:44:15,120
And if you look carefully...

662
00:44:15,200 --> 00:44:19,640
maybe we did indeed make
a couple of little changes.

663
00:44:22,160 --> 00:44:25,560
- No Krafayis.
- No Krafayis.

664
00:45:02,320 --> 00:45:03,880
(WHISTLES)

665
00:45:05,440 --> 00:45:09,240
If we had got married, our kids
would have had very, very red hair.

666
00:45:11,680 --> 00:45:13,680
The ultimate ginger.

667
00:45:15,560 --> 00:45:17,800
The ultimate ginge.

668
00:45:22,520 --> 00:45:24,600
Brighter than sunflowers.

